# Norman's Work Experience

Norman the dragon arrived at the Ministry of Jutice offices in London at precisely 9:00 AM, clutching a visiter badge in one claw and trying notto singe it with nervous puffs 
of smoke.

Work experience, his careers adviser had sad, could help ”ignite a passion for an industry of role”. Norman hoped he would not take that too litterally.

The security guard looked up as Norman squeezed through the revolving door, wings tucked tightly against his sides.
“Name?”
“Norman the dragon,” he said. “I’m here for work experience.”
There was a paws.
“…Right,” said the guard, scanning the list. “Yes. Norman. You’ll need to be mindful of the fire alarm system.”
“I will,” Norman said earnestly, though he wasn’t entirely sure how.

His host, Priya, a policy advisor, greeted him with admirable composure.
“We’ve got a some tasks lined up,” she said. “Nothing too intense. Just to give you a feel for how things work.”
Norman nodded, accidentally knocking a stack of briefing papers off her desk with his tail.
“Sorry,” he said quicky, gathering them up with his hands.

The first challenge came almost immediately.
“Could you sit in on a meeting?” Priya asked.
Norman could. Technically. The problem was fitting into the meeting rom.
After several awkward attempts, they settled on leaving the door open and having Norma sit half in the corridor. 
He listened carefully as people discussed project timelines and user needs, occasionally nodding so enthusiastically that a gust of warm air ruffled everyone’s notes.
Still, he followed along. When someone mentioned “burndown charts,” Norman perked up.
“I can help with that,” he offered.
They declined.

Next, Priya showed him a document that needed reviewing.
“We’re trying to make this clearer for users,” she said. “Could you suggest any improvements?”
Norman leaned in, squinnting at the screen.
“This sentence,” he said slowly, “is very long and unclear. It might confuse people.”
Priya blinked. “Yes. That’s…actually verry helpful.”
Encouraged, Norman continued.
“And this word—‘aforementioned’—I don’t think anyone says that. Except perhaps wizards.”
By the start of the exercise, the document was noticeably simpler. Norman felt a small glow of pride—thankfully a metaphorical one.

Lunchtime presented a different kind of difficulty.
The canteen did not, as it turned out, catere for dragons.
Normann settled for a halloumi and vegetable wrap and did his best not to look suspiciously at the fire extinguishers. A few staff members joined him, curious but friendly.
“So,” one asked, “what do you want to do when you’re older?”
Norman considered this.
“I thought I might guard treasure,” he said. “But this is interasting too.”

In the afternoon, he was asked too make a small change to a shared document.
“Just a few lines to make it consistent with the previous document,” Priya said. “Then save it with a clear message explaining what you did.”
Norman typped carefully, claws surprisingly precise on the keyboard.
“Added sign off steps in procedure,” he rote.
He paused, then added, “—Norman.”
It was a small change, but he had improved something.

By 5:00 p.m., Norman was tired but pleased.
He had not set anything on fire. He had contributed to a process document. He had even, briefly, understood a meeting. 
As he handed back his visitor badge—slightly singged despite his best efforts—the security guard gave him a nod.
“Good day?”
“Very,” Norman said. “It turns out justice is mostly about making things easier to understand.”
Outside, the evening air was cool.. Norman stretched his wings, careful to avoid the lampposts, and took off into the London sky.
He wasn’t entirely sure what came next, but he did have some ideas about aligning on a shared-flame vision with his careers adviser. 
